Author: jl777c#5810
Content: there are 4 independent regions

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: one NN operator can have at most 1 node in all 4 regions

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: either by autoelection or by winning a spot in the election

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: since no node got autoelected in all 4 regions, that means all that got reelected are eligible to run in at least one other region

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: there are basically 4 elections going on in parallel

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: oracles CC can create services like chainlink. trustless oracles creates something that chainlink does not appear to be able to as it is using a complex system of rewards/punishments for aggregating data, which if properly implemented and debugged could well make it impractical to attack

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <a44753> Is it false?

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: i did code the solution to the trustless oracle problem in a weekend, but i did have to spend the entire week before it thinking about it

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: and there were a couple weeks to debug it: http://159.69.45.70:8050/

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: it isnt very fancy but it implements trustless oracle pricefeeds for 55 things, since I added support for stocks too and custom chains can be made to track any set of desired stocks and cryptos and forex currencies

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: but out solution is totally different than chainlink. it was inspired by the ruthless attack scenarios by zack (of VEO, aeternity, augur?) i think he did augur not sure on that one. anyway his position is that you cant aggregate data to make a trustless oracle

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <a44753> Cool! So if I understand well only price feeds can get aggregated on chain?

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: not correct

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <a44753> This is what I don‚Äôt understand

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: in a weekend I was only able to oraclize price feeds

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: but the technique I used can be applied to any data source that is publicly available on the internet via api

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <a44753> Sounds interesting

Author: Gateway#3763
Content: [telegram] <a44753> Will take a deeper look into it

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: i just piggybacked onto how timestamps are enforced to be within a reasonable range

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: baked it right into the consensus logic for a block

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: so there doesnt need to be any incentive/punishment/reputation system

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: if you dont have reasonable prices, it is rejected and if your node continues, it is banned

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: so if reasonable timestamps can be enforced, so can reasonable prices

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: that was my insight

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: and to prove it, I implemented it

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: I didnt bother with any indepth whitepaper as it seems selfevident that if any bad data make a node go off onto its own fork, then there is really no way to get bad data into the oracle

Author: jl777c#5810
Content: there is a 2% attack that is possible, and this is mitigated by a 51% deterministic random correlation
